{"timestamp": "2026-07-11T01:13:57.752892+00:00", "level": "INFO", "logger": "llm_policy_library.orchestrator", "message": "query answered", "correlation_id": "b561d472-369d-47f0-9a8d-510ad13ea574", "query": "What controls apply to API security?", "answer": "Applicable controls from the supplied set for API security are:\n\n- Require developer-produced security and privacy architecture and design that specifies required security functionality and how controls are allocated and integrated across components, so APIs are designed with explicit security behavior and unified protections [sa-17].\n\n- Require interactive application security testing by the developer to identify and document application-level flaws, which applies to API implementations and helps find API-specific vulnerabilities (eg. injection, auth flaws) during development [sa-11.9].\n\n- Uniquely identify and authenticate system services and applications before establishing communications, which applies directly to APIs and requires that services and applications calling or serving APIs be identified and authenticated prior to interacting [ia-9].\n\n- Require applications to assert the access they need at installation, provide enforcement mechanisms to prevent unauthorized access, and approve access changes after installation. For APIs this means enforcing declared access rights and preventing unauthorized API access or privilege escalation [ac-3.12].\n\n- Use single-device access to allow connections from one device to platforms/applications/data in different security domains while preventing information flow between domains. This can be applied to API gateway or proxy configurations that mediate cross-domain API access and enforce domain separation [ac-4.22].\n\nIf you need mapping of specific API controls (e.g., rate limiting, input validation, OAuth scopes) to these items, the supplied controls do not explicitly cover those specifics; they cover design/testing, service authentication, application access assertion/enforcement, and single-device cross-domain access [sa-17][sa-11.9][ia-9][ac-3.12][ac-4.22].", "latency_ms": 6913.3, "documents": 5, "citations": ["sa-17", "sa-11.9", "ia-9", "ac-3.12", "ac-4.22"], "is_fallback": false}
